<Layout title="What I'm up to lately" description="Building my product Baselife with Claude">
  <div class="metadata">
    <time datetime="2026-05-25">Updated May 25, 2026, from Verlé in Saint Petersburg</time>
  </div>
  <header>
    <h1 id="title">What I'm up to lately</h1>
  </header>
  <section>
    <h2>Looking for interesting job</h2>
    <p>14 years in design. I'm applying to AI product companies, ideally in physical and mental health, productivity tools, or journaling areas.</p>
    <p>I want to grow in the skills that matter most to me: AI-first product thinking, business mindset, systems thinking, refined aesthetics.</p>
    <p>I do my best work where the problem isn't defined yet, building something useful from zero.</p>
  </section>
  <section>
    <h2>Building Baselife MVP</h2>
    <p>Earlier this year <a href="/baselife-naming" class="link">I renamed the project</a>, registered the domain, and launched <a href="https://baselife.me/" class="link" target="_blank">a landing page</a> to collect early sign-ups.</p>
    <p>My cofounder and I are now assembling the core flow and preparing for launch.</p>
    <p>In parallel I'm building knowledge bases for myself and the project, putting together a design system, touching every adjacent craft by hand. In a corporation, daily metric meetings slowly numb your design sense. Working across everything brings it back.</p>
  </section>
  <section>
    <h2>Reassembling my identity</h2>
    <p>I've outgrown the designer identity. "Founder" still feels too early.</p>
    <p>I'm trying "builder", it fits the work I do outside of design.</p>
    <p>Whatever name fits will keep changing. That's just the phase.</p>
  </section>
  <section>
    <h2>Writing regularly</h2>
    <p>I've kept <a href="https://t.me/initsrightplace" class="link" target="_blank">a Telegram channel</a> since 2019. Before that, <a href="https://medium.com/@IngMaeSing" class="link" target="_blank">Medium</a> from 2016, and earlier some small blogs on Egeya and Bookmix.</p>
    <p>For years writing felt like performance, like I had to construct someone before I could have an opinion. But the desire was always mine. As a kid I watched my grandfather and wanted to be a writer when I grew up.</p>
    <p>I let the performance go and learned to write regularly. Unemployment helps.</p>
    <p>Now I'm developing my voice and learning to think better. Writing is how I think, design, and study. Through collabs and new conversations, I'm figuring out what I actually want to say.</p>
  </section>
  <section>
    <h2>Researching journaling practices</h2>
    <p>I want to map the full landscape: journals, life calendars, self-tracking. Every practice people use to live a longer, fuller life.</p>
    <p>This isn't just curiosity. You have to design yourself before you can design products for anyone else.</p>
  </section>
  <section>
    <h2>Mentorship on goal-setting</h2>
    <p>My self-design framework is free to use in both <a href="/ld" class="link">English</a> and <a href="https://t.me/initsrightplace/255" class="link" target="_blank">Russian</a> versions. With or without me.</p>
    <div class="paragraph-with-list-block">
      <p>
        From coaching I know outside help works. I can help you:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          find what you actually want, and write it as a vision,
        </li>
        <li>
          break the vision into concrete, reachable goals,
        </li>
        <li>
          build one coherent system to move toward them daily.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <p>I can also help with design and career. 14 years in the craft, across bigtech and startups.</p>
    <p>If you want to work together, <a href="https://t.me/IngMaeSing" class="link" target="_blank">write me on Telegram</a>.</p>
  </section>
</Layout>

